{
  "doc_id": "40318",
  "text": "In its simplest form, epistasis captures the phenotypic effect of one SNP being conditional on the allelic state of another SNP. Interlocus interactions are common and have been demonstrated to occur both within [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and between genes (reviewed in [CITATION_6] . Epistatic interactions can help to explain why some organisms express genetic variants and others do not, e.g., in the same way that disease-causing mutations in humans do not affect all people equally [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . As a result, epistasis is a complex phenomenon that is very challenging to characterize [CITATION_9] because the epistatic interactions cannot be predicted (in magnitude or direction) by single SNPs in isolation.",
